{"title_page": "John Strachey (journalist)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2016}}\n[[File:John St Loe Strachey.jpg|thumb|John St Loe Strachey]]\n'''John St Loe Strachey''' (9 February 1860 \u2013 26 August 1927), was a [[United Kingdom|British]] journalist and newspaper proprietor.\n\n==Life==\nStrachey was the second son of [[Sir Edward Strachey, 3rd Baronet]], and his wife Mary Isabella (n\u00e9e Symonds),<ref name=EB1922>{{Cite EB1922 |wstitle=Strachey, John St. Loe |volume=32 |page=579}}</ref> and the brother of [[Edward Strachey, 1st Baron Strachie]], and [[Henry Strachey (artist)|Henry Strachey]]. He was educated at [[Eton College]] and [[Balliol College, Oxford]],<ref name=EB1922/> and later [[called to the Bar]], but chose to take up journalism as his profession.<ref name=EB1922/> Between 1887 and 1925, he was editor of ''[[The Spectator]]''. He was a close friend and confidant of the diplomat, [[Cecil Spring Rice|Sir Cecil Spring Rice]], with whom he corresponded for many years.<ref name=burton>{{cite book|last=Burton|first=David Henry|title=Cecil Spring Rice: A Diplomat's Life|year=1990|location=Page 22|publisher=Fairleigh Dickinson Univ Press|isbn=978-0-8386-3395-3|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kCGKtLkHnxAC&source=gbs_navlinks_s}}</ref>\n\nStrachey also edited (1896\u20131897) ''[[The Cornhill Magazine]]''.<ref name=EB1922/>\n\nStrachey's son [[John Strachey (politician)|John]] became a [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] politician and government minister.\n\nHis daughter Amabel married the architect [[Clough Williams-Ellis]].\n\n== Publications ==\n* ''The Adventure of Living : a Subjective Autobiography'', [https://archive.org/details/theadventureofli06567gut]\n\n==See also==\n*[[Strachey Baronets]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/36340?docPos=1|title=Strachey, John St Loe|publisher=[[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]]|date=2004|accessdate=2017-07-25}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Gutenberg author|id=2087}}\n* {{Internet Archive author |sname=John St Loe Strachey |birth=1860 |death=1927 }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-media}}\n{{succession box | before=[[R. H. Hutton]] | title=Editor of ''[[The Spectator]]''| years=1887 - 1925 | after=[[Evelyn Wrench]] }}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Strachey, John St. Loe}}\n[[Category:1860 births]]\n[[Category:1927 deaths]]\n[[Category:People educated at Eton College]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Balliol College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:British male journalists]]\n[[Category:Younger sons of baronets]]\n[[Category:Strachey family|John (journalist)]]\n[[Category:People of the Victorian era]]\n[[Category:Deputy Lieutenants of Surrey]]\n\n{{UK-journalist-stub}}\n{{England-painter-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2016}}\n[[File:John St Loe Strachey.jpg|thumb|John St Loe Strachey]]\n'''John St Loe Strachey''' (9 February 1860 \u2013 26 August 1927), was a [[United Kingdom|British]] journalist and newspaper proprietor.\n\n==Life==\nStrachey was the second son of [[Sir Edward Strachey, 3rd Baronet]], and his wife Mary Isabella (n\u00e9e Symonds),<ref name=EB1922>{{Cite EB1922 |wstitle=Strachey, John St. Loe |volume=32 |page=579}}</ref> and the brother of [[Edward Strachey, 1st Baron Strachie]], and [[Henry Strachey (artist)|Henry Strachey]]. He was educated at [[Eton College]] and [[Balliol College, Oxford]],<ref name=EB1922/> and later [[called to the Bar]], but chose to take up journalism as his profession.<ref name=EB1922/> Between 1887 and 1925, he was editor of ''[[The Spectator]]''. He was a close friend and confidant of the diplomat, [[Cecil Spring Rice|Sir Cecil Spring Rice]], with whom he corresponded for many years.<ref name=burton>{{cite book|last=Burton|first=David Henry|title=Cecil Spring Rice: A Diplomat's Life|year=1990|location=Page 22|publisher=Fairleigh Dickinson Univ Press|isbn=978-0-8386-3395-3|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kCGKtLkHnxAC&source=gbs_navlinks_s}}</ref>\n\nStrachey also edited (1896\u20131897) the [[Cornhill Magazine]].<ref name=EB1922/>\n\nStrachey's son [[John Strachey (politician)|John]] became a [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] politician and government minister.\n\nHis daughter Amabel married the architect [[Clough Williams-Ellis]].\n\n== Publications ==\n* ''The Adventure of Living : a Subjective Autobiography'', [https://archive.org/details/theadventureofli06567gut]\n\n==See also==\n*[[Strachey Baronets]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/36340?docPos=1|title=Strachey, John St Loe|publisher=[[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]]|date=2004|accessdate=2017-07-25}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Gutenberg author|id=2087}}\n* {{Internet Archive author |sname=John St Loe Strachey |birth=1860 |death=1927 }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-media}}\n{{succession box | before=[[R. H. Hutton]] | title=Editor of ''[[The Spectator]]''| years=1887 - 1925 | after=[[Evelyn Wrench]] }}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Strachey, John St. Loe}}\n[[Category:1860 births]]\n[[Category:1927 deaths]]\n[[Category:People educated at Eton College]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Balliol College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:British male journalists]]\n[[Category:Younger sons of baronets]]\n[[Category:Strachey family|John (journalist)]]\n[[Category:People of the Victorian era]]\n[[Category:Deputy Lieutenants of Surrey]]\n\n{{UK-journalist-stub}}\n{{England-painter-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Judgtastic", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLife:mce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Strachey_(journalist)"}
{"title_page": "List of U.S. states and territories by life expectancy", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikimedia list article}}\n[[File:Life Expectancy By State.png|thumb|403x403px|Life Expectancy by state in 2017 by the Measure of America]]\nThis article presents a '''list of United States [[U.S. state|states]] and [[Territories of the United States|territories]] sorted by their [[life expectancy]]''' at birth and by race/ethnicity in every state where the population of that racial or ethnic group is sufficiently large for robust estimates. The data in the 2017 column is taken from the [[Institute for Health Metrics and Evaluation]] for the states (2017 data),<ref name=\"IHME50\"/><ref name=\"NatGeo1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalgeographic.com/culture/2018/12/life-expectancy-united-states/|title=If you're an average American, you'll live to be 78.6 years old|date=December 7, 2018|website=Culture}}</ref> and from the [[CIA World Factbook]] for the territories (2018 data).<ref name=\"Factbook1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/aq.html|title=The World Factbook \u2014 Central Intelligence Agency|website=www.cia.gov}}</ref><ref name=\"Factbook2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/rq.html|title=The World Factbook \u2014 Central Intelligence Agency|website=www.cia.gov}}</ref><ref name=\"Factbook3\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/vq.html|title=The World Factbook \u2014 Central Intelligence Agency|website=www.cia.gov}}</ref><ref name=\"Factbook4\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/gq.html|title=The World Factbook \u2014 Central Intelligence Agency|website=www.cia.gov}}</ref><ref name=\"Factbook5\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/cq.html|title=The World Factbook \u2014 Central Intelligence Agency|website=www.cia.gov}}</ref> Data in the 2010 columns comes from [[Measure of America|Measure of America's]] third national human development report, ''The Measure of America 2013\u20132014''.<ref name=\"MOA2013_2014\">{{cite web|url=http://www.measureofamerica.org/measure_of_america2013-2014/|title=The Measure of America 2013\u20132014 \u2014 Measure of America: A Program of the Social Science Research Council|website=www.measureofamerica.org|access-date=2016-12-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.measureofamerica.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/06/MOA-III.pdf |title=Data |website=www.measureofamerica.org |format=PDF}}</ref> Overall, life expectancy at birth in [[Hawaii]], [[Puerto Rico]] and [[California]] are among the longest in the nation, while life expectancy at birth in [[Mississippi]] and [[American Samoa]] are among the shortest in the nation.\n\nThe life expectancy in some states has fallen in recent years; for example, Maine's life expectancy in 2010 was 79.1 years, and in 2018 it was 78.7 years. ''[[The Washington Post]]'' noted in November 2018 that overall life expectancy in the United States was declining although in 2018 life expectancy had a slight increase of 0.1.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/health-science/us-life-expectancy-declines-again-a-dismal-trend-not-seen-since-world-war-i/2018/11/28/ae58bc8c-f28c-11e8-bc79-68604ed88993_story.html|title=U.S. life expectancy declines again, a dismal trend not seen since World War I - The Washington Post}}</ref>\n[[File:Life Expectancy by county (2).png|thumb|311x311px|Life Expectancy by County in 2018 by the Robert Wood Johnson Foundation Program]]\n<br />\n\n\n\n\n\n== Robert Wood Johnson Foundation Rankings (2018) ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable mw-collapsible\"\n|+\n!Rank\n!State/Federal District\n!Life Expectancy 2018<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://measureofamerica.org/maps/?state^life_expect^all_all^Health^health|title=Measure of America report 2018|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|ar